        -:  429:  //  2 - it is faster than simply by-passing the heap allocation through stack allocation.
        -:  430:  //  3 - it makes this fallback consistent with the heavy GEMM routine.
        -:  431:  //  4 - it fully by-passes huge stack allocation attempts when multiplying huge fixed-size matrices.
        -:  432:  //      (see https://stackoverflow.com/questions/54738495)
        -:  433:  // For small fixed sizes matrices, however, the gains are less obvious, it is sometimes x2 faster, but sometimes x3 slower,
        -:  434:  // and the behavior depends also a lot on the compiler... This is why this re-writing strategy is currently
